Inputs → Weights → Summation → Activation Function → Output
=====

Single Perceptron (Single Layer Perceptron)

A Single Perceptron is the most basic type of Artificial Neural Network (ANN).

It contains:

Input layer
One neuron/output node
No hidden layer

It is mainly used for simple yes/no classification problems

=======

Simple Diagram
X1 ----\
        \
X2 ------> [ Perceptron ] ---> Output
        /
X3 ----/

Where:

X1, X2, X3 = Inputs
Weights = Importance of each input
Output = Final prediction
Real-Time Example
Example: Pass or Fail Prediction

Suppose:

Study Hours
Attendance

are given as inputs.

Input:
Study Hours = 8
Attendance = 90%

The perceptron checks these values and predicts:

Output = PASS

If low marks and low attendance:

Output = FAIL
How Single Perceptron Works
Step 1: Take Inputs

Example:

X1 = Study Hours
X2 = Attendance
Step 2: Multiply by Weights

Each input has importance.

Weighted Sum = (X1 × W1) + (X2 × W2)
Step 3: Activation Function

Perceptron decides:

If value > threshold → 1
Else → 0
1 = PASS
0 = FAIL
Very Simple Real-Life Analogy
Job Interview Selection

HR checks:

Communication skill
Technical skill

If both are good:

Selected = YES

Else:

Selected = NO

This yes/no decision is similar to a Single Perceptron

=============

Important Features

| Feature      | Description           |
| ------------ | --------------------- |
| Layers       | Single layer          |
| Hidden Layer | Not present           |
| Output Type  | Yes/No                |
| Used For     | Simple classification |
| Example      | Spam/Not Spam         |


==========

Limitation

Single perceptron can solve only linear problems.

It cannot solve complex problems like:

XOR problem
Image recognition
Speech recognition

===========

Single Perceptron is the simplest ANN model that makes a simple binary decision using inputs and weights

